		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30707465">I recently picked up The Melancholy of Haruhi Suzumiya when it was released on Kindle, sort of on an impulse, but found it to be much more enjoyable than I expected based on my previous viewing of the (2006) anime.  One of the things that becomes lost in the transition to visual media is the idea of authorial voice--and voice is such a huge part of what makes the Haruhi novels interesting.  The main thing that kept me reading is the fact that Kyon was such a fun character to follow.  There are so many scenes in the anime which are flat-out boring that become incredibly entertaining when viewed directly from the perspective of Kyon's headspace.<br />
<br />
I don't particularly care for the plot; the early arcs do benefit from an accompanying sense of awe and discover as you're learning about the way the universe works,, but eventually the story enters a regular cadence which oscillates between amusing and boring.  The general dullness is owed in large part to a general lack of chemistry between the characters.  Despite the fact that the main cast has five characters, all of the characters apart from Kyon feel rather bland apart from their superficial eccentricities.  (Just being an alien or a time traveler doesn't automatically qualify a character as interesting.)</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
