		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message30722865"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>lpf said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>@Kuiper: If you ever find the time to, I think you would be providing some of the most interesting analysis in the club so far if you took some specific examples of scenes that were better in the novel for the reasons you suggested and pasted the raw text alongside subbed screenshots from the anime so that we can know exactly what you mean.<!--quote--></div><br />
The problem with the screenshot comparison point is that screenshots fail to highlight a significant part of what makes anime scenes boring, which is often that they simply take too much screen time to convey too little information.  Duration doesn't really come across in a screenshot.<br />
<br />
On a fundamental level I think the issue with the visual medium is that it's essentially a third-person presentation.  As a requirement for this kind of presentation, you basically have things split between events and introspection.  Stuff is shown on screen, and then we cut away to Kyon monologuing about the thing that he just saw.  Whereas in a first-person narration, literally everything that happens comes through Kyon's voice so we see bits of his character and personality injected through his description of the events around him, rather than seeing a dichotomy of "world inside Kyon's head/events outside Kyon's head."<br />
<br />
For a quick example of what I'm talking about, watch the beginning of the first episode of the anime (first in chronological order, not broadcast order), just the first 2:30 leading up to the OP, including the part where Haruhi first introduces herself.  Then compare it to the opening of the first novel (available in the free Kindle reading sample): <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Melancholy-Haruhi-Suzumiya-ebook/dp/B007UTNPH4" target="_blank" rel="nofollow"><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Melancholy-Haruhi-Suzumiya-ebook/dp/B007UTNPH4" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.amazon.com/Melancholy-Haruhi-Suzumiya-ebook/dp/B007UTNPH4</a></a><br />
<br />
By the end of the Haruhi introduction, we've learned so much more about Kyon's character and how he sees the world than the anime conveys in roughly the same amount of time.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
